.SHORT TERM...
Issued at 105 AM PDT Tue Jul 21 2026
(Today and tonight)

Isolated to widely scattered high based showers mainly continue
over the coastal waters and the Bay Area. A few reports via social
media and webcams Monday showed patchy light sprinkles resulting
in a mix of trace reports and a couple isolated 0.01". Almost all
of the forecast area has remained dry. The precipitable water (pw)
on late Monday afternoon`s Oakland upper air sounding was 1.42",
the max moving average for July 20. Earlier over the weekend
Saturday evening`s pw was 0.50", 10th percentile. Deep southerly
winds currently transporting remnant tropical moisture into the
forecast area is largely distributing the moisture between 15,000
feet and 26,000 feet. Between 15,000 feet and the ground, the layer
is relatively drier, likely resulting in some evaporation of rain
drops before reaching the ground.

No lightning has been observed so far over our forecast area,
including no lightning activity since Sunday evening over the
Pacific all the way out across the remnants of Elida. An ASCAT
wind pass at 0511z (10:11 pm PDT Monday) showed the remnant
surface low pressure circulation ~ 500 miles southwest of Monterey
with winds 15 to 30 knots with a few higher gusts to 35 knots.
The surface low center will slowly fill and weaken while moving
northward. The area out ahead of the low has pw upwards of 1.50"
to 1.60" which is not far from the July daily maximum pw (1.74")
on the period record since 1948. This pw arrives today and
forecast soundings show this will continue to be largely
distributed in the middle to upper troposphere. The highest mid to
upper level pw will be in our area when there is weak positive
vorticity at and above the 500 mb level this afternoon/evening
otherwise negative vorticity will be present in the 700-500 mb
layer. Given model trends, a lack of lightning seen so far,
temporary weak positive vorticity at and above 500 mb and weak
convergence at 250 mb later today, it`s a persistence forecast
today. The atmosphere is very complex though, could it still
convect and produce an isolated lightning strike? Yes. Stay tuned
to the latest updates.

00z GFS and ECMWF forecast the 700-500 mb layer drying out
tonight. However, elevated pw will remain from the surface to
lower levels.

The recent increase in pw (water vapor) will largely slow radiational
cooling through morning, possibly slowing how warm it gets today too
as well, though lower level temperatures around the 925 mb level are
forecast to increase a few degrees Celsius today. Daytime highs may
get above normal today, varying from the 70s/80 coastside to the 80s
bayside and 90s/100 far inland.

